Socioeconomic inequalities in disability-free life expectancy (DFLE) exist 
across all European countries, yet the driving determinants of these differences 
are not completely known. We calculated the impact on educational inequalities 
in DFLE of equalizing the distribution of eight risk factors for mortality and 
disability using register-based mortality data and survey data from 15 European 
countries for individuals between 35 and 80 years old. From the selected risk 
factors, the ones that contribute the most to the educational inequalities in 
DFLE are low income, high body-weight, smoking (for men), and manual occupation 
of the father. Potentially large reductions in inequalities can be achieved in 
Eastern European countries, where educational inequalities in DFLE are also the 
largest.

